# Changelog

## [1.0.0] - 2026-07-20

### Added

- Extracted ssm as a standalone binary from the dots project
- Rich terminal user interface built with ratatui and crossterm
- Session management: add, edit, delete SSH sessions via a TUI form
- Secure password storage using the OS keychain (macOS Keychain, Linux Secret Service)
- SSH_ASKPASS mechanism for zero-exposure password handling
- One-time-nonce Unix domain socket for password delivery
- SSH config import from ~/.ssh/config with wildcard block filtering
- Tags system with comma/space-separated tags and tag-based filtering
- ProxyJump (jump host) support per session
- Live TCP reachability probing with latency sparklines
- Biometric unlock support (fprintd on Linux, Touch ID stub on macOS)
- 7 built-in themes: auto, noir-cat, knew-pines, catppuccin, gruvbox, nord, tokyo-night
- Vim-style keybindings with numeric prefix support (e.g. 5j)
- Clipboard yank for user@host (pbcopy, xclip, xsel)
- Direct connect mode via `ssm -c user@host[:port]`
- Session list output via `ssm --list`
- SSH config import via `ssm --import`
- Auto-reload when sessions.json changes externally
- Which-key menu system for settings and theme switching
- Minimum terminal size guard (50x10)
- Integration tests and end-to-end SSH_ASKPASS tests
- CI/CD with GitHub Actions for lint, test, and cross-platform release builds

### Changed

- Separated from the dots project into its own independent repository and binary
- Configuration directory moved to ~/.config/ssm/
- Session storage uses JSON with passwords excluded from disk (keychain only)

### Security

- Passwords are never stored in plaintext on disk
- Passwords are served via SSH_ASKPASS with one-time-nonce socket protection
- Serve-once semantics prevent brute-force loops on wrong passwords
- Selective prompt answering: only passwords, never key passphrases or host key confirmations
- Automatic migration from legacy JSON that stored plaintext passwords
